PRINTING CODE. Amendments: Whenever an existing statute (or a section of the Indiana
Constitution) is being amended, the text of the existing provision will appear in this style type,
additions will appear in this style type, and deletions will appear in this style type.
Additions: Whenever a new statutory provision is being enacted (or a new constitutional
provision adopted), the text of the new provision will appear in this style type. Also, the
word NEW will appear in that style type in the introductory clause of each SECTION that adds
a new provision to the Indiana Code or the Indiana Constitution.
Conflict reconciliation: Text in a statute in this style type or this style type reconciles conflicts
between statutes enacted by the 2025 Regular Session of the General Assembly.
SENATE BILL No. 200
A BILL FOR AN ACT to amend the Indiana Code concerning
education.
Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the State of Indiana:
1 SECTION 1. IC 20-26-5-4.1 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
2 AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY
3 1, 2026]: Sec. 4.1. (a) This section applies to a vendor contract
4 entered into, amended, or renewed after June 30, 2026.
5 (b) As used in this section, "choice of law provision" means a
6 provision, a clause, a covenant, or an agreement that is contained
7 in, collateral to, or affecting a vendor contract that purports to
8 make the vendor agreement subject to the laws of another state.
9 (c) As used in this section, "indemnity provision" means a
10 provision, a clause, a covenant, or an agreement that:
11 (1) is contained in, collateral to, or affecting a vendor
12 contract; and
13 (2) purports to indemnify, defend, or hold harmless, or has the
14 effect of indemnifying, defending, or holding harmless, a
15 vendor against liability for loss or damage resulting from:
16 (A) negligence;
17 (B) intentional acts; or
2026 IN 200—LS 6948/DI 152

2
1 (C) omissions;
2 of the vendor or an agent, employee, servant, or independent
3 contractor that is directly responsible to the vendor.
4 (d) As used in this section, "vendor contract" means a contract
5 between a governing body of a school corporation and a vendor in
6 which the vendor promises to provide goods or services.
7 (e) Notwithstanding any other law, an indemnity provision in a
8 vendor contract under this section is:
9 (1) against public policy; and
10 (2) void and unenforceable.
11 (f) Notwithstanding any other law, a choice of law provision in
12 a vendor contract under this section is:
13 (1) against public policy; and
14 (2) void and unenforceable.
15 SECTION 2. IC 20-26-20-4, AS ADDED BY P.L.86-2020,
16 SECTION 5, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
17 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 4. (a) Upon request by an organization under
18 section 3 of this chapter, a public school shall provide at least one (1)
19 time two (2) times each school year, a day and time, which may be
20 during the school day or at a time where a majority of students and
21 their families will be present on school property, as approved by the
22 public school, for the representatives of the organization to provide
23 information to students on school property as described in section 3 of
24 this chapter.
25 (b) An organization may submit a grievance to the department,
26 in a manner prescribed by the department, if a public school
27 refuses to allow an organization to provide information to students
28 on school property as required by subsection (a).
29 (c) If the department determines a public school improperly
30 refused an organization under this section, the public school shall
31 be subject to a state tuition support monthly distribution reduction
32 of one thousand dollars ($1,000) until the school allows the
33 organization to provide information to students on school property
34 as required by subsection (a). A public school is not entitled to
35 recover the state tuition support lost as a result of a reduction
36 described in this subsection.
